column7: How to Escape the Ad-Hoc Data Request Trap - 4 Mindset Shifts From a Former Director Of Analytics
column9:
View this post on the web at https://seattledataguy.substack.com/p/how-to-escape-the-ad-hoc-data-request

Over the past few weeks, Iâ€™ve been running a series of webinars with experienced data leaders, folks with decades of hands-on experience. 
One of those sessions was titled â€œFrom Reactive to Proactive: Managing Stakeholders to Unlock Strategic Data Work.â€
It turned into a standout conversation with Celina Wong [ https://substack.com/redirect/19179f51-a05f-4462-8bbe-4b8fc5bf125a?j=eyJ1IjoiNTFkc2s3In0.TG_s5GaRal_EYLFDF-UYKHL5eEiDcX8TdL6-5nynlYA ], whoâ€™s led data teams at companies like Ulta and Poppins and recently served as CEO of a data consulting firm. We dug into a problem that nearly every data team wrestles with.
Too often, data teams get stuck in reactive cycles, pulling data, building dashboards, and answering questions as they come. Over time, that leads to hundreds (or thousands) of assets that no one actually uses. Worse, a lot of them were never aligned to the business strategy in the first place.
So how do you break the cycle?
How do you shift your data team from reactive responders to strategic partners?
When Youâ€™re Reactive, You Donâ€™t Actually Have Influence
Letâ€™s start with the big question:
Why should your data team shift from reactive to proactive?
Is it even worth it for your company?
In most cases, yes, absolutely. Because staying reactive traps your team in a low-leverage, low-impact cycle.
Hereâ€™s what that looks like:
Youâ€™re always behind: By the time you ship the dashboard [ https://substack.com/redirect/8fc003df-20df-42f3-9eb5-00d7bd22f428?j=eyJ1IjoiNTFkc2s3In0.TG_s5GaRal_EYLFDF-UYKHL5eEiDcX8TdL6-5nynlYA ] or answer the question, the conversation has already moved on. 
You canâ€™t prioritize: Everything feels urgent when you're not aligned to broader goals. There's no clear filter for what's worth doing.
Youâ€™re seen as just an input output machine: Stakeholders bring you pre-baked solutions because they see you as a tool. Just a input output machine.
You have zero influence: Yes, your team might be seen as helpful, but not essential. If the business could self-serve straight from the warehouse, they would. In their eyes, youâ€™re just middleware between them and the answers they need for their strategic initiatives.
So, how do you break out of that trap and become more proactive?
Care About the Business, Not Just the Stakeholder
One of the most common patterns [ https://substack.com/redirect/e0f3d14a-2da5-4a4d-8278-e63913f21146?j=eyJ1IjoiNTFkc2s3In0.TG_s5GaRal_EYLFDF-UYKHL5eEiDcX8TdL6-5nynlYA ] on data teams? Over-accommodation.
Someone asks a question, and the team rushes to answer it. It sounds helpful, but it keeps you locked in a reactive cycle.
The bigger issue? A lot of those requests donâ€™t actually move the business forward [ https://substack.com/redirect/b4bbeead-07c8-4154-895a-0ca6d0357948?j=eyJ1IjoiNTFkc2s3In0.TG_s5GaRal_EYLFDF-UYKHL5eEiDcX8TdL6-5nynlYA ]. Theyâ€™re not tied to strategy. Theyâ€™re not aligned with company goals. Sometimes, theyâ€™re just a VP trying to position themselves ahead of a meeting.
So hereâ€™s the first mindset shift:
Stop thinking about serving the stakeholder. Start thinking about serving the business as a whole.
That perspective helps you evaluate: Should we do this at all?
It also makes it easier to say â€œno.â€ And while that wonâ€™t always win you fans, the longer youâ€™re in the organization, and the more trust and influence you buildâ€”the more you earn the right to push back.
Anticipate What the Business Needs
Data teams often stay hyper-focused on tooling [ https://substack.com/redirect/39174beb-bcff-492f-836c-ae3a150f304e?j=eyJ1IjoiNTFkc2s3In0.TG_s5GaRal_EYLFDF-UYKHL5eEiDcX8TdL6-5nynlYA ], chasing the latest feature drop, or obsessing over architecture. But in doing so, we sometimes miss whatâ€™s happening outside our own bubble.
Celina put it perfectly in our conversation:
As an IC, yes, it makes sense to go deep on tech. You want to know the tools, master the queries, and keep up with what Snowflake [ https://substack.com/redirect/12b7a061-252f-43b7-913d-b0021ba22a78?j=eyJ1IjoiNTFkc2s3In0.TG_s5GaRal_EYLFDF-UYKHL5eEiDcX8TdL6-5nynlYA ], BigQuery [ https://substack.com/redirect/e7af3585-2f82-4a85-bd24-bb59eb599fdf?j=eyJ1IjoiNTFkc2s3In0.TG_s5GaRal_EYLFDF-UYKHL5eEiDcX8TdL6-5nynlYA ] or dbt [ https://substack.com/redirect/43d899d9-0a5d-429c-a56e-b63daeb7e470?j=eyJ1IjoiNTFkc2s3In0.TG_s5GaRal_EYLFDF-UYKHL5eEiDcX8TdL6-5nynlYA ] released last week.
But as you grow into a more strategic [ https://substack.com/redirect/9f5ee6ee-1fca-4c81-8174-2e11a96ca631?j=eyJ1IjoiNTFkc2s3In0.TG_s5GaRal_EYLFDF-UYKHL5eEiDcX8TdL6-5nynlYA ] and proactive role, your value shifts. You need to pay just as much attention to whatâ€™s going on in your industry as you do to whatâ€™s happening in your stack.
Thatâ€™ll be the second mindset shift and thatâ€™s also how you get a seat at the table.
Start tracking:
Industry trends
Customer sentiment
Business model shifts
Emerging risks and regulations
When you show up to a meeting already thinking like this, you can say:
â€œHey, based on recent shifts in (cost of acquisition or perhaps impressions on a new social platform), our team has already analyzed the data and noted an opportunity to grow a new segment.â€
Now youâ€™re going beyond just answering questions. Youâ€™re taking a stand and showing you care about the business.
SeattleDataGuyâ€™s Newsletter is a reader-supported publication. To receive new posts and support my work, consider becoming a free or paid subscriber.
Give Your Boss What Their Boss Needsâ€¦Think Beyond Yourself
Donâ€™t just do what your boss asks. Think about what theyâ€™re going to do with it.
Itâ€™s easy to stop at the task in front of you, not because you lack initiative, but because you donâ€™t always know what else needs to be done.
Celina shared this third great mindset shift:
Start asking not only what your boss wants, but why. Whatâ€™s the end use? Who are they trying to influence?
In many cases, that dashboard or report isnâ€™t for internal analysis. Itâ€™s going straight to an executive update or board deck. Sometimes, they just need a sound bite to impress the C-suite.
So ask!
â€œWhoâ€™s this for?â€
â€œHow will this be used?â€
â€œWhat are they trying to decide or prove?â€
Once you start thinking one level up, you can better package what you deliver. Celina mentioned that some of the metrics and taglines she delivered ended up in C-suite talking points, and eventually in news publications.
This shift doesnâ€™t just help you deliver better work.
It also gives you more clarity on when to say no!
If youâ€™re feeling stuck on what to communicate Jordan Cutler  has a great article titled The 5 levels of communicating impact as an engineer [ https://substack.com/redirect/87dd87f1-bedb-4cf2-aea1-40d543552c20?j=eyJ1IjoiNTFkc2s3In0.TG_s5GaRal_EYLFDF-UYKHL5eEiDcX8TdL6-5nynlYA ] you should read.
Strategy Is What You Say No To
Instead of final thoughts, Iâ€™ll end with this forth and final mindset shift from Celina. 
Strategy is what you say no to.
Another way Iâ€™ve heard this said is that:
Strategy is what you DO, not what you SAY.
You canâ€™t be a strategic partner to the business if youâ€™re always reacting. Reacting means you havenâ€™t defined what matters. You havenâ€™t set boundaries around what you will or wonâ€™t take on.
So you take on everything.
You become the accommodating data team. You donâ€™t want to offend anyone. You want to be helpful. You want to be liked.
And the reactive cycle continues.
As always, thanks for reading!
Join My Technical Consultants Community
If youâ€™re a data consultant or considering becoming one then you should join the Technical Freelancer Community! We have over 1900 members!
Youâ€™ll find plenty of free resources you can access to expedite your journey as a technical consultant as well as be able to talk to other consultants about questions you may have!
Articles Worth Reading
There are thousands of new articles posted daily all over the web! I have spent a lot of time sifting through some of these articles as well as TechCrunch and companies tech blog and wanted to share some of my favorites!
The Politics of Data Warehousing
Data warehousing projects are frequently side-tracked or derailed completely by non-technical factors, in particular the political treaty lines within the firm, and the politicized nature of data itself. 
Because data warehouses are infrastructure for sociotechnical systems (STSs) within the firm, politics and the exercise of power are inherent in data warehousing projects, and data warehouse designers have to adopt work practices and methods from non-technical disciplines, think of themselves in new ways, and employ some fairly sophisticated qualitatively sociological methods in order to optimize the chances for successful deployment of data warehouses.
Read More Here [ https://substack.com/redirect/3fc3c983-3577-4b7e-8039-b456a3e49ad6?j=eyJ1IjoiNTFkc2s3In0.TG_s5GaRal_EYLFDF-UYKHL5eEiDcX8TdL6-5nynlYA ]
Apache Iceberg Isn't Coming To Save You
Maybe Iâ€™m biased. I love new tools. Like many technophiles, Iâ€™m drawn to new solutions. Yet, I still feel I need to pause and question when a new tool is posed as the savior of the data world.
Many people are searching for a silver bullet and assume it must be a new piece of technology. And vendors love itâ€”they lean in. They coin new terms, repackage old ones, and flood the space with â€œbest practicesâ€ and design patterns built to hook our curiosity.
And letâ€™s be honest: part of what drew many of us to tech in the first place was the appeal of solving complex problems. Nothing scratches that itch like a new tool packed with just enough nuance and edge cases to unravel.
But lately, Iâ€™ve been asking myself a different questionâ€”especially when it comes to technologies like Apache Iceberg:
Do we even know what problem weâ€™re trying to solve?
Read More Here [ https://substack.com/redirect/c1ccd350-eeaa-4c67-b7bd-53751f4186a9?j=eyJ1IjoiNTFkc2s3In0.TG_s5GaRal_EYLFDF-UYKHL5eEiDcX8TdL6-5nynlYA ]
End Of Day 188
Thanks for checking out our community. We put out 4-5 Newsletters a month discussing data, tech, and start-ups.
If you enjoyed it, consider liking, sharing and helping this newsletter grow!

A while ago, I stumbled on the idea of the â€œother 8 hoursâ€ in Arnold Bennettâ€™s timeless book â€œHow to Live on 24 Hours a Dayâ€ (https://djX7c204.eu1.hubspotlinks.com/Ctc/5H+113/djX7c204/VWhj044ZS0RyW6ZVGrj7MGpt7W35KrPN5nnfSvN6-TNZM3pyd0W6N1vHY6lZ3nWW850bZv3vS9DcW2JsQmy1jBm55W1C703Q8x1c2tW5jJr5Q4BJlQ6W8HSWL48pq8f8W5lY6Sr7l5z5KW8xcccd7bsfH-W82wkfK38hvzrW4Wm2ZB2z_RdkW3DzPNl3k65jwW2l2tKn68Qt8tW4hB_YQ91n6lbV9gYj-7ghPYwW6YWkrX8FVfJgW247Q-_91K2D0W3JQJW55HZsB7W2r1cCc5xLS9SW7BjHgb70vLWzW6hyLqz868MZsW8z7VB16wwzGYW4Xcn9X96ZkQLW7tQH_n1-1Yp6dnD4DF04 ) . Hereâ€™s a quote that I love:

So let us begin to examine the budget of the dayâ€™s time. You say your day is already full to overflowing. How? You actually spend in earning your livelihoodâ€”how much? Seven hours, on the average? And in actual sleep, seven? I will add two hours, and be generous. And I will defy you to account to me on the spur of the moment for the other eight hours.

In the book, our friend Arnold breaks down our daily 24 hours into three segments:

The first 8 hours - Sleep. Even the richest person in the world needs to sleep.

The next 8 hours - Work. Everyone needs to work. If youâ€™re employed, you work. If youâ€™re an entrepreneur, you work. If youâ€™re a trust fund baby, you want to work. If youâ€™re a parent, you do the work of the family and the household. If youâ€™re free from having to work, youâ€™re likely to eventually realise that you want to work anyway because it gives your life purpose.

But then we have the other 8 hours - for everything else.

What do we do with the other eight hours? How we use the other 8 hours is the difference between a life that we love, and a life that we donâ€™t.

If Iâ€™m not intentional, itâ€™s easy for the other 8 hours to look like this

- 2 hours playing World of Warcraft

2 hour scrolling on social media or watching YouTube videos

A few hours scrolling on the internet

A few more hours eating and chilling

And boom. Just like that, the other 8 hours are gone.

My ideal way of spending these other 8 hours actually looks something more like this:

- Learning (2 hours): dedicated time to learn something new - a language, guitar, music theory, coding a website, etc.
- Health (2 hours): going to the gym, taking long walks, playing padel and squash with the gang ;)
- Something social (3 hours): chilling and spending quality time with family and friends; hosting dinner parties
- Solo time (1 hour): journalling, reflecting, other things that people say are good for the soul (whatever that means)

Have a great week!

Ali xx

Lesson 26: Data Dictionaries
ðŸŽ¥ Video [ https://substack.com/redirect/e3db6474-f194-44b9-8855-a59785a494e2?j=eyJ1IjoiNTFkc2s3In0.TG_s5GaRal_EYLFDF-UYKHL5eEiDcX8TdL6-5nynlYA ]
Today weâ€™re talking about one of the sexist parts of Data Analytics: Data Documentation ðŸ¥µðŸ”¥ðŸ˜®â€ðŸ’¨
ðŸ”—Grab the Big SQL Energy Beginner Data Dictionary here [ https://substack.com/redirect/b2c7e289-da6a-4702-8392-5b67819dc3fd?j=eyJ1IjoiNTFkc2s3In0.TG_s5GaRal_EYLFDF-UYKHL5eEiDcX8TdL6-5nynlYA ]
You might be laughing, but I promise you: data documentation is a huge luxury in the real world, so if youâ€™re lucky enough to get it, be grateful. The real world can be really messy and a lot times, thereâ€™s no documentation for databases and tables. It can be really challenging to find what you need and understand what each table contains. More importantly, it can be really challenging to understand how all the tables connect together which is necessary knowledge for joiningâ€” which weâ€™ll learn a little later!
Data dictionaries are exactly what they sounds like. Theyâ€™re a centralized source of truth within an organization where all the information about the data is stored. Itâ€™s a guide on what tables are available, whatâ€™s in each table, and what you can expect from each column. Sometimes companies use fancy tools for data documentation or even something as simple as Confluence or Excel sheets. It really depends on the size of the company and the size of the investment in data documentation! Iâ€™ve worked at mostly startups, so to even get an Excel sheet was an exciting thing for me LOL! Many data sources (like CRMs) that are ETLed (Extract Transform Load) into your database may even have their own data documentation online you can use. 
Data dictionaries will usually have some or all of the following information: 
Column names
Data types: each columnâ€™s data type
Field description: a definition of the column
Allowed Values: what type of values can be in the column (ex. closed list of values, strings of length 2, etc.)
Data source or lineage: where the data comes from and how it got there, any transformations or modifications it has
The team that owns the data: who you can reach out to if you need help of updates
Other notes and useful info!
Remember, not all companies will even have data dictionaries at all, but it could be worth advocating for within your company for the most-used tables, especially if youâ€™re training someone new soon. Having a single source of truth and a place to look up columns can be really useful for someone. 
Data documentation isnâ€™t the most sexiest thing to do, but itâ€™s the boring stuff that can be the most important long term! See you in the next lesson!

column7: Back To The Basics: What Is Columnar Storage
column9:
View this post on the web at https://seattledataguy.substack.com/p/back-to-the-basics-what-is-columnar

Hi, fellow future and current Data Leaders; Ben here ðŸ‘‹
Over the past few months Iâ€™ve been writing a series focused on going back to the basics. Iâ€™ve covered most of the various steps in an ETL/ELT as well as did some deeper dives into SQL.
Below are the links to the fuller series, but in this article, weâ€™ll be focused on columar storage.
Back To The Basics
Data Pipelines
Data Sharing in the Real World: Why SFTP Remains Essential for Companies [ https://substack.com/redirect/5db5f7f2-8bb0-435d-ba78-b1dab79fcb86?j=eyJ1IjoiNTFkc2s3In0.TG_s5GaRal_EYLFDF-UYKHL5eEiDcX8TdL6-5nynlYA ]
>From Basics to Challenges: A Data Engineer's Journey with APIs [ https://substack.com/redirect/71e711c1-b5fe-42ca-8dca-49ed88ab7842?j=eyJ1IjoiNTFkc2s3In0.TG_s5GaRal_EYLFDF-UYKHL5eEiDcX8TdL6-5nynlYA ]
Understanding the â€œTâ€ in ETL: A Back-to-Basics Guide to Data Transformations [ https://substack.com/redirect/732cdd74-ff53-49a0-a323-5e166764dbd8?j=eyJ1IjoiNTFkc2s3In0.TG_s5GaRal_EYLFDF-UYKHL5eEiDcX8TdL6-5nynlYA ]
ðŸ”’ Why Your Data Pipeline Probably Isnâ€™t Production-Ready [ https://substack.com/redirect/71372cf9-3dad-4092-9a72-9da140da6ddd?j=eyJ1IjoiNTFkc2s3In0.TG_s5GaRal_EYLFDF-UYKHL5eEiDcX8TdL6-5nynlYA ]
SQL Basics
Behind the Scenes of SQL: Understanding SQL Query Execution [ https://substack.com/redirect/65970424-2a9c-465a-bd27-dcfd0ea8a16c?j=eyJ1IjoiNTFkc2s3In0.TG_s5GaRal_EYLFDF-UYKHL5eEiDcX8TdL6-5nynlYA ]
Back To The Basics With SQL: Understanding Hash, Merge, and Nested Joins [ https://substack.com/redirect/e48919b7-c0f8-477e-b439-e8f6f3bf3845?j=eyJ1IjoiNTFkc2s3In0.TG_s5GaRal_EYLFDF-UYKHL5eEiDcX8TdL6-5nynlYA ]
ðŸ”’ Best Practices for Simplifying Complex SQL [ https://substack.com/redirect/f2d35394-6031-498e-9b0e-571af6a693dc?j=eyJ1IjoiNTFkc2s3In0.TG_s5GaRal_EYLFDF-UYKHL5eEiDcX8TdL6-5nynlYA ]
With that out of the way, letâ€™s jump into it!
Intro
Data engineers often discuss columnar storage, especially when discussing data warehouses or file formats like Parquet.
But why does it matter?
Why is columnar storage such a big deal for analytics? What makes it so well-suited for analytical use cases compared to other formats?
Maybe you already have a rough idea.
This article will help further explain columnar storage, why itâ€™s used, and how it compares to row-based storage. It will also look at the most common formats and real-world use cases.
Letâ€™s dive in.
What Is Columnar Storage?
To understand columnar storage, it helps to start with how it compares to row-based storage. Most databases donâ€™t really make this distinction obvious; you just run SQL [ https://substack.com/redirect/e48919b7-c0f8-477e-b439-e8f6f3bf3845?j=eyJ1IjoiNTFkc2s3In0.TG_s5GaRal_EYLFDF-UYKHL5eEiDcX8TdL6-5nynlYA ] queries and get results. However, in the background, how the data is stored matters.
Letâ€™s break down the difference between row-based and column-based storage.
Row-Based Storage
In row-based storage, data is stored one row at a time.
Imagine a table of customer orders with the following columns: order_id, product, order_date, and amount.
When an end-user places an order, the database inserts all of that data as a single row:
Row-based storage is optimized for transactional systems when you need to quickly read or write a full record. For example, when inserting a new order or updating an existing one.
As that information comes in, it is far more beneficial to store it in a row. That way, itâ€™s quick to insert and update.
Columnar Storage
In columnar storage, data is stored by column instead of row by row.
Using the same order example, a columnar format would store the data like this:
This works great for analytics. When you run queries that aggregate or filter by a few columns (think asking a question like â€œWhatâ€™s the average order amount for the past month?â€), columnar storage reduces the amount of data scanned and significantly improves performance.
Thatâ€™s why analytical databases like BigQuery, Vertica, Snowflake [ https://substack.com/redirect/773b556f-213c-43dd-8bef-9ecda8df27c9?j=eyJ1IjoiNTFkc2s3In0.TG_s5GaRal_EYLFDF-UYKHL5eEiDcX8TdL6-5nynlYA ], and Redshift are built with columnar storage under the hood.
I remember first really learning about the benefits of columnar storage and compression, for example, when I was digging into Redshift a decade ago. Of course, this begs the question...why?
Why Columnar Storage Matters for Analytics
"Not every data warehouse [ https://substack.com/redirect/4ccfcea9-4519-4f09-9a2b-d14077170442?j=eyJ1IjoiNTFkc2s3In0.TG_s5GaRal_EYLFDF-UYKHL5eEiDcX8TdL6-5nynlYA ] (OLAP) is necessarily a column store: traditional row-oriented databases and a few other architectures are also used." 
- Designing Data-Intensive Applications [ https://substack.com/redirect/073bb431-17a9-4afc-bee0-34423a490db3?j=eyJ1IjoiNTFkc2s3In0.TG_s5GaRal_EYLFDF-UYKHL5eEiDcX8TdL6-5nynlYA ]
DDIA is right; not every OLAP [ https://substack.com/redirect/3303aa78-7445-4453-b2a3-e516f284b496?j=eyJ1IjoiNTFkc2s3In0.TG_s5GaRal_EYLFDF-UYKHL5eEiDcX8TdL6-5nynlYA ] system has to use column storage. I actually got into a slight spat during an interview once when the interviewer insisted all data warehouses  [ https://substack.com/redirect/b718c210-0a8a-4ffb-a3b6-8f00304789b9?j=eyJ1IjoiNTFkc2s3In0.TG_s5GaRal_EYLFDF-UYKHL5eEiDcX8TdL6-5nynlYA ]must use columnar storage.
That said, there are clear reasons we go through the trouble of using columnar storage formats for analytics. Hereâ€™s why it matters.
SeattleDataGuyâ€™s Newsletter is a reader-supported publication. To receive new posts and support my work, consider becoming a free or paid subscriber.
Performance
One of the goals of analytical queries is to process large swaths of data. Perhaps you want to analyze millions or billions of events. Well, when you run a query that only touches two out of ten columns, youâ€™ll only read the relevant columns(based on your query). That means you scan less data and minimize disk I/O.
In contrast, row-based systems often must read the entire row, even if you only need a single field.
Compression
Because columnar formats store data of the same type together (all order_date values in one block), they compress much more effectively.
Of course, there are multiple methods of compression. Here are a few you might encounter if you look under the hood of your data analytics platform.
Run-Length Encoding (RLE): Stores a repeated value once, along with the number of times it appears consecutively.
Original column: A, A, A, A, B, B, B, C
RLE encoded: (A,4), (B,3), (C,1)
Dictionary Encoding: Builds a dictionary of unique values and stores smaller reference keys instead of the full value. Similar to the image above, but if it helps, you can view it as:
Original column: Red, Green, Red, Blue, Red, Green
Dictionary: {0: Red, 1: Green, 2: Blue}
Encoded: 0,1,0,2,0,1
Bit-Packing: Compresses small numeric values using only the minimum number of bits needed.
Delta Encoding: Stores the difference between consecutive values instead of the full values. Thus, the delta is part of delta encoding.
Vectorized Processing 
Columnar storage unlocks a technique called vectorized execution, where operations are applied to batches of column values at once, instead of one row at a time.
This enables query engines (like DuckDB, Presto, and Spark) to use SIMD (Single Instruction, Multiple Data) CPU instructions, which can perform the same calculation across dozens or hundreds of values in a single cycle.
For example, instead of evaluating price > 100 on each row individually, a vectorized engine processes the entire column segment in one shot.
Parallelism
Since each column is stored separately, systems can read multiple columns in parallel.
This is especially valuable with large datasets. Modern architectures can spread the workload across multiple CPU cores or nodes, speeding things up even further.
Common Columnar File Formats
Regarding columnar storage, much of the complexity is abstracted away. If you're using a cloud data warehouse, youâ€™re not interacting with the file format directly; youâ€™re just querying the data.
But under the hood, these formats can make a massive difference in performance and cost. Later in this article, Iâ€™ll share an example of where switching compression methods significantly improved a company's query speeds and storage efficiency.
Even if youâ€™re not choosing the file format, these systems rely heavily on columnar storage principles.
That said, when you have control over the format, like when setting up a data lake(house), it helps to know your options. Here are some of the most common ones:
Parquet
Apache Parquet [ https://substack.com/redirect/fc94ce91-cc3d-4104-b7ee-50700024eb06?j=eyJ1IjoiNTFkc2s3In0.TG_s5GaRal_EYLFDF-UYKHL5eEiDcX8TdL6-5nynlYA ], developed at Twitter and Cloudera in 2013 [ https://substack.com/redirect/e4b9d126-1552-41a0-b9ce-f315361602e1?j=eyJ1IjoiNTFkc2s3In0.TG_s5GaRal_EYLFDF-UYKHL5eEiDcX8TdL6-5nynlYA ], and was designed to offer a more efficient columnar format for big data analytics. It builds on ideas from Trevni and Google's Dremel paper.
Now if you ever look into the structure of a parquet file, itâ€™ll likely be a little confusing. The term row, column and page get thrown around so you might be wondering what they are all referring to.
Here are some of the key structural components of a Parquet file:
Row Group â€“ The largest unit of work; a horizontal partition of the data. Each row group contains all columns for a subset of rows.
Column Chunk â€“ A column within a row group. This enables column-wise compression and encoding.
Page â€“ The smallest unit of data storage within a column chunk. Each page is encoded and compressed independently. There are typically:
Data Pages â€“ Contain the actual values.
Dictionary Pages â€“ Used for dictionary encoding if applicable.
Footer â€“ Located at the end of the file; stores metadata like schema, row groups, compression info, and statistics for efficient reads.
These components allow engines like Spark, Trino [ https://substack.com/redirect/d0d8cc8f-f665-4f3c-a1a2-45d88687943e?j=eyJ1IjoiNTFkc2s3In0.TG_s5GaRal_EYLFDF-UYKHL5eEiDcX8TdL6-5nynlYA ], and BigQuery to skip over irrelevant data and only read whatâ€™s necessary.
Parquet [ https://substack.com/redirect/3df41360-a066-424a-8a11-43d7dbdd3465?j=eyJ1IjoiNTFkc2s3In0.TG_s5GaRal_EYLFDF-UYKHL5eEiDcX8TdL6-5nynlYA ] uses a hybrid encoding approach that combines techniques like dictionary encoding, run-length encoding (RLE), and bit-packing to maximize storage efficiency and reduce I/O during reads.
Itâ€™s also the most common file format I come across(when a client isnâ€™t just building on top of what their data warehouse provides).
ORC
Apache ORC  [ https://substack.com/redirect/f51ea564-8f37-42c0-aed1-59a05508fcd2?j=eyJ1IjoiNTFkc2s3In0.TG_s5GaRal_EYLFDF-UYKHL5eEiDcX8TdL6-5nynlYA ](Optimized Row Columnar) was built as a Hadoop-native file format focused on deeper compression, efficient storage, and built-in indexing to speed up analytical queries. It became popular with tools like Hive and often outperforms older formats like RCFile.
Similar to Parquet, there are several terms youâ€™ll need to understand if you were to look under the hood of an ORC file.
Stripes â€“ The largest unit in an ORC file. Each stripe contains rows and is independently compressed and indexed.
Row Index â€“ Allows skipping over data blocks that donâ€™t meet query criteria.
Stripe Footer â€“ Contains column-level metadata and statistics like min/max, count, and null values.
File Footer â€“ Stores global metadata including schema definitions, column encodings, and file-level statistics.
Postscript â€“ Contains information about compression algorithms and versioning.
I was also going to write a little bit about Arrow, but since there is some nuance there I am going to hold out for this article. In the future Iâ€™ll have to write a deeper article about the actual formats themselves. Because I didnâ€™t even dive into concepts like pages and row groups. Although Vu Trinh  has a great article on Parquet. [ https://substack.com/redirect/5010f6f0-da68-4cda-b863-c2e1e860fa5f?j=eyJ1IjoiNTFkc2s3In0.TG_s5GaRal_EYLFDF-UYKHL5eEiDcX8TdL6-5nynlYA ]
Real-World Use Cases
You should have a good idea of what columnar storage is and why it can be useful. Now letâ€™s see it be useful.
Letâ€™s look at a few real-world examples of companies using Parquet files at scale.
In one case, Uber was already using Parquet and improved performance by switching compression methods. In another, Criteo was processing billions of events per day and migrated to Parquet for better flexibility and efficiency.
Now, before you decide your 100GB or 1TB warehouse needs to switch to Parquet, take a moment. Both of these companies are operating at petabyte scale. The lessons are useful, but the context matters.
Uber Switching To ZSTD For Compression
Back in 2022 [ https://substack.com/redirect/332c645b-ef86-493c-907b-d60da512e345?j=eyJ1IjoiNTFkc2s3In0.TG_s5GaRal_EYLFDF-UYKHL5eEiDcX8TdL6-5nynlYA ], Uber published a detailed article about how they use Parquet and how switching compression methods helped improve performance.
As you can imagine Uberâ€™s data platform manages hundreds of petabytes, with Apache Parquet as the primary storage format.
As data volumes grew, so did storage and compute costs. To address this, Uber focused on reducing file sizes at the Parquet level. By switching from SNAPPY and Gzip to Zstandard (ZSTD) compression, they achieved up to 39% smaller file sizes and improved query performance by lowering vCore usage.
They also built tools for high-throughput column deletion and column reordering, which allowed them to prune unused fields and optimize encoding. 
I for some reason found the quote:
When a table is created, table owners can create whatever columns they want, as there is no governance on that. But some of them might not be used, and those unused columns took a lot of space. We found that just one table after removing unused columns, there were PB level data savings.
Somewhat comical. But perhaps thatâ€™s because I know so many companies that could save money and time removing columns, dashboards and other unused data team artifacts.
Overall, the result of this work led to lower storage costs, faster queries, and no sacrifice in data integrity.
Many of those improvements, including ZSTD integration and column pruning tools, were contributed back to the open-source Apache Parquet project.
SeattleDataGuyâ€™s Newsletter is a reader-supported publication. To receive new posts and support my work, consider becoming a free or paid subscriber.
Parquet Format At Criteo
Criteo [ https://substack.com/redirect/08a844f0-04a6-4c35-9a6c-af4205684b2e?j=eyJ1IjoiNTFkc2s3In0.TG_s5GaRal_EYLFDF-UYKHL5eEiDcX8TdL6-5nynlYA ], a major player in display retargeting, processes roughly 30 billion events per day and reaches 840 million users monthly, creating massive data processing demands.
Historically, they used RCFile for their Hadoop data but found it deeply tied to Hive and difficult to integrate with their broader stack (Cascading, Pig, Spark, etc.). To improve flexibility and performance, Criteo migrated nearly a petabyte of actively used data from RCFile to Apache Parquet.
Parquet offered better native support across modern processing engines and improved compression, saving substantial storage while maintaining, or even improving, query performance. In their IO-bound cluster, benchmarks showed that Parquet compressed with Gzip matched or exceeded RCFile performance, with added storage efficiency.
By switching to Parquet, Criteo unlocked faster analytics, reduced storage needs, and gained the flexibility to use any compute engine, paving the way for future improvements as they scaled with tools like Impala.
I wonder if they are still using Impalaâ€¦
Final Thoughts
Columnar storage was built to process analytical queries. Between its ability to compress data efficiently and streamline large-scale processing, itâ€™s easy to see why so many companies lean on it to power their data warehouses and lakehouses.
That said, if your data footprint is relatively small, you can probably get by just fine with your existing setup. Donâ€™t let FOMO push you into rearchitecting just for the sake of using the â€œlatestâ€ infrastructure.
As always, thanks for reading.

Hey friends,

This week, I wanted to share another pretty cool thing that I learned at one of Joe Hudson's Art of Accomplishment (https://djX7c204.eu1.hubspotlinks.com/Ctc/5H+113/djX7c204/VWx8LB7p0nGDW6dMppl7x-hBRW7bJF9w5mT48PN9k7M9W3pyd0W7lCdLW6lZ3nZW2S9M254PPjR4W1t9syQ5JX5SnW1ZGh3S6k-GNnW37KSX4147Tr0W1JRn0n83wqXHW1bnXk11K8kQlW8dc6Zw4rNtyPW1Twnp65JLc_XW7sndHR5Bxg6XW583RnS6M4SplW6gsGKP1BW1Z5W8SxPjk77843TVd-bP-3r1vCGW5wPSdM6v5-jZW8GbZlH6mbSYPW35m8Bh2hyhC6W8mvLGC594xN5W2Q4Fwg7rdYPfW35z1fB7B_hbHW6HsDn92yx2VpW2hppLd6q5lYyW2RKTrG7pY44hW2njXqr8tRyl5W85XrYS4LYW-Df7gfDcl04 ) retreats (which I've been going on about for the past few weeks).

It's called "The Pleasure Game" - and even though it was just a 10-minute exercise during our 7-day retreat, it's one of those things that's really stuck with me.

Here's how it works:

For the next 10 minutes, you challenge yourself to feel as much pleasure as you possibly can in whatever you're doing. That's it. The only goal is to feel pleasure.

When they introduced this at the retreat, I found myself:

- Taking a deep breath and noticing how nice it felt to just... breathe
- Getting up from the couch and appreciating how it felt to move my body
- Walking outside and feeling the warmth of sunlight on my skin
- Touching a tree and experiencing the texture of bark under my fingertips
- Sitting in a nearby chair and noticing how good it felt to just... sit
- Playing with my wedding band and enjoying both how it looked and felt (plus the nice memory of my wife who wasn't there with me)

When the bell rang to signal the end of our 10 minutes, I had this weird moment of "oh wait, I don't want this to be over" - which is pretty wild considering I was basically doing nothing. My only goal was to feel pleasure.

But here's where it gets interesting...

Since the retreat, I've been playing this game more and more in my daily life. While washing dishes, I'll challenge myself: "How can I feel more pleasure in this moment?" When I'm just sitting on the sofa or having a meal, same question: "How can I feel more pleasure right now?"

I'm actually writing this while on a walk (speaking into VoicePal (https://djX7c204.eu1.hubspotlinks.com/Ctc/5H+113/djX7c204/VWx8LB7p0nGDW6dMppl7x-hBRW7bJF9w5mT48PN9k7Mbv3pyd0W8wLKSR6lZ3q1W7rjl594fgGldW3-4lmc1x3ynQW4FDmDv8c2fk9W1TZKNT6FQvF2W6_tm_78C86YjW1gK3Mr4J4Y4BW686Zlq6vG-F9N6xvr-GR2pFkW2n0BqQ6-S4VZW1q7PpP6M0_NdW26hDDq1RR9slW3yZb2Q4rZ8dPW5cWcnr7C2W7CW4GrTSb7LM8W5W3lwT1-7lt9STN248HnwSLwfSW65985-7ZSCvsN3Cm4GP8LKt4W7m4fbp7rbtRHVBClr41zJzq_W33QclZ7rjhz9N5DGgtg_bT7JW6chPqG8HCdTYW6qZ8_M2FvgfHW4kGFDS3G795wW5N0n4h3gYj15Vvqx8V1WF1BbW7srC7k4fRBsJf7lLBcP04 ) , the app my team and I built to make writing more fun ðŸ˜‰). I've been walking for about 20 minutes with my AirPods in, just speaking thoughts out loud which the app transcribes. But even as I'm saying these words, just priming my brain to feel more pleasure makes me notice:

- The wind on my skin
- Getting unexpectedly sprayed by a sprinkler (and how refreshing that feels)
- The ground under my feet
- How powerful my legs feel
- The beautiful scenery around me

Here's the cool thing about the pleasure game - it's always available to us. In every moment, you can create this little partition in your brain with just one goal: feel as much pleasure as possible right now.

You can play it:

- While working at your computer
- During household chores
- When eating food
- Even while taking a dump (yep, he went there)

In every moment, there's so much more pleasure available than what we usually default to. But often, all it takes to enjoy ourselves more is to just set that as an intention. I forget this a lot, but I'm trying to remind myself more and more.

Have a great week!

Ali xx
